{"title_page": "Bradnop railway station", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n | name = Bradnop\n | image = \n | caption =\n | coordinates = {{coord|53.0910|-1.9860|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n | gridref = SK010548\n | original    = [[North Staffordshire Railway]]\n | postgroup   = [[London Midland and Scottish Railway]]    \n | locale = [[Bradnop]], [[Staffordshire]]\n | borough = [[Staffordshire Moorlands]]\n | platforms = 1\n | years = 5 June 1905\n | events = Opened{{sfnp|Quick|2009|p=96}}\n | years3 = 30 September 1935\n | events3 = Closed to passengers{{sfnp|Quick|2009|p=96}}\n | years4 = 4 May 1964\n | events4 = Closed to freight{{sfnp|Jeuda|1980|p=68}}\n}}\n\n'''Bradnop railway station''' was a [[railway station]] that served the village of [[Bradnop]], [[Staffordshire]]. It was opened by the [[North Staffordshire Railway]] (NSR) in 1905 and closed to passenger use in 1935,{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=304}} but remained open to freight traffic until 1964.{{sfnp|Jeuda|1980|p=68}}\n\n==Construction and opening==\nThe station was on the NSR branch from [[Leek Brook railway station|Leekbrook Junction]] to {{rws|Waterhouses|Staffordshire}}.  The single line branch was authorised on 1 March 1899 by the ''Leek, Caldon Low, and Hartington Light Railways Order, 1898''.<ref>{{cite hansard | url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1899/mar/21/light-railways-act-1896 |title=Light Railways Act 1896 | house=House of Commons | date=21 March 1899 | column=1552}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27062 |page=1761 |date=14 March 1899 }}</ref> and construction took several years.\n\nThe station at Bradnop was built in a [[Cut (earthmoving)|cutting]] on the long gradient from Leek Brook to Ipstones, digging the cutting required the excavation of {{convert|500000|cuyd|m3}} of material to create a cutting {{convert|1|mile|km|1}} long and, at its deepest, {{convert|60|ft|m|1}} deep.{{sfnp|Jeuda|1980|p=19}}\n\n==Station layout==\n[[File:Bradnop Station (remains) - geograph.org.uk - 1878328.jpg|thumb|left|The station site in 1962 showing the goods yard high above the main running line]]\nThe station had a single platform and limited goods facilities.{{sfnp|Jeuda|1980|p=70}} Although the station buildings and passenger platform were in a cutting, the small goods yard was constructed at the top of the bank and this necessitated quite a steep gradient in the track leading from the branch line to the good yard.{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=57}} A [[passing loop]] was installed and Bradnop was a [[block section]] with {{rws|Ipstones}} and Leek Brook East signalboxes,{{sfnp|Jeuda|1980|p=71}} although Bradnop itself was not equipped with a signal box, only a [[ground frame]].{{sfnp|Christiansen|1997|p=56}}\n\nIn NSR days the station staff comprised a [[Station Master]], 1 [[Porter (railroad)|porter]] and 1 porter/[[Signalman (rail)|signalman]].{{sfnp|Jeuda|1980|p=73}}\n\nThe station buildings were of wooden construction and had to be rebuilt following a fire in April 1926 which destroyed the original building.{{sfnp|Jeuda|2014|p=151}}\n\n==Closure==\nThe branch line was never a financial success and passenger services were withdrawn on 30 September 1935.{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=258}} The station remained open as a goods station until May 1964 when all traffic on the branch except mineral worksings from Caldon Low quarries was withdrawn.{{sfnp|Jeuda|1980|p=68}}\n\n== The site today ==\nMineral trains to Caldon Low continued until 1989 when the line was [[:wikt:mothball#verb|mothballed]].  In 2009 Moorland and City Railways purchased the line with the intention of reopening the line to mineral traffic from the quarry.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.heritagerailway.co.uk/news/steaming-back-to-cauldon-lowe |title=Steaming back to Cauldon Lowe |newspaper=Heritage Railway |date=25 November 2010}}</ref> In 2014 this plan was placed on hold as the [[Competition Commission]] ruled that [[Lafarge Tarmac]] must sell one of its sites, possibly Caldon Low, so the heritage railway, the [[Churnet Valley Railway]], are seeking to purchase the line themselves.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.leek-news.co.uk/LJ-Trains/story-20797980-detail/story.html |title=Leek railway line moves a step closer |newspaper=Leek Post & Times |date=12 March 2014 |access-date=23 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419015833/http://www.leek-news.co.uk/LJ-Trains/story-20797980-detail/story.html |archive-date=19 April 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Route==\n{{Historical Rail Start}}\n{{rail line|previous={{rws|Ipstones}}<br><small>[[Waterhouses branch line|Waterhouses branch]]</small>|col=800000 |next={{rws|Leek}}<br><small>[[Churnet Valley Line]]</small>|route=[[North Staffordshire Railway]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{Quick-Stations |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Christiansen |first1=Rex |last2=Miller |first2=Robert William |title=The North Staffordshire Railway |year=1971 |publisher=David & Charles |location=[[Newton Abbot]], [[Devon]] |isbn=0-7153-5121-4 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Christiansen |first1=Rex |title=Portrait of the North Staffordshire Railway|year=1997|publisher=Ian Allan |location=[[Shepperton]], [[Surrey]] |isbn=0-7110-2546-0 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last1=Jeuda |first1=Basil |title=The Leek, Caldon & Waterhouses Railway |year=1980 |publisher=North Staffordshire Railway Company (1978) |location=[[Cheddleton]], [[Staffordshire]]|isbn=0-907133-00-2 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Jeuda |first=Basil |title= The North Staffordshire Railway in LMS days |volume=3 |publisher= Lightmoor Press |location=[[Lydney]], [[Gloucestershire]] |year=2014 |isbn=978-1899889-83-9 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Closed stations Staffordshire}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bradnop Railway Station}}\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1905]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1935]]\n[[Category:Former North Staffordshire Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Staffordshire Moorlands]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n | name = Bradnop\n | image = \n | caption =\n | coordinates = {{coord|53.0910|-1.9860|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n | gridref = SK010548\n | original    = [[North Staffordshire Railway]]\n | postgroup   = [[London Midland and Scottish Railway]]    \n | locale = [[Bradnop]], [[Staffordshire]]\n | borough = [[Staffordshire Moorlands]]\n | platforms = 1\n | years = 5 June 1905\n | events = Opened{{sfnp|Quick|2001|p=96}}\n | years3 = 30 September 1935\n | events3 = Closed to passengers{{sfnp|Quick|2001|p=96}}\n | years4 = 4 May 1964\n | events4 = Closed to freight{{sfnp|Jeuda|1980|p=68}}\n}}\n\n'''Bradnop railway station''' was a [[railway station]] that served the village of [[Bradnop]], [[Staffordshire]]. It was opened by the [[North Staffordshire Railway]] (NSR) in 1905 and closed to passenger use in 1935,{{sfnp|Christiansen|Miller|1971|p=304}} but remained open to freight traffic until 1964.{{sfnp|Jeuda|1980|p=68}}\n\n==Construction and opening==\nThe station was on the NSR branch from [[Leek Brook railway station|Leekbrook Junction]] to {{rws|Waterhouses|Staffordshire}}.  The single line branch was authorised on 1 March 1899 by the ''Leek, Caldon Low, and Hartington Light Railways Order, 1898''.<ref>{{cite hansard | url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1899/mar/21/light-railways-act-1896 |title=Light Railways Act 1896 | house=House of Commons | date=21 March 1899 | column=1552}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27062 |page=1761 |date=14 March 1899 }}</ref> and construction took several years.\n\nThe station at Bradnop was built in a [[Cut (earthmoving)|cutting]] on the long gradient from Leek Brook to Ipstones, digging the cutting requi